Abstract

The deployment of 100B+ parameter Large Language Models (LLMs) on edge computing devices has long been strictly constrained by two physical limitations: the "memory capacity wall" and the "memory access bandwidth wall". Targeting hardware platforms with 48GB unified memory and high-speed NVMe SSD (taking Apple M4 Pro as the benchmark), this paper proposes a bottom-up system-level inference framework. The framework integrates an `mmap`-based SSD-RAM dynamic paging scheduling mechanism, the TurboQuant 3-bit polar orthogonal cache compression algorithm, 2-bit extreme weight quantization based on Incoherence Processing, and a draft-free multi-branch speculative decoding architecture. Theoretical deduction and underlying architecture analysis show that this scheme can compress the memory footprint of 100B-level Dense models and 120B-level Mixture of Experts (MoE) models within the safe threshold of physical memory. Under the constrained memory bandwidth of 273 GB/s, it achieves high-throughput autoregressive generation of 20+ tokens/s for Dense models and 50+ tokens/s for sparse models, while significantly suppressing the high-frequency random write wear of solid-state drives.


---
1. Introduction

With the exponential growth of the parameter scale of large language models, their deployment on resource-constrained edge devices faces two basic physical challenges:

1. Capacity Bound: A 100B model occupies about 55GB of storage space under conventional 4-bit quantization, which not only exceeds the physical limit of 48GB unified memory, but also its Key-Value Cache (KV Cache), which grows linearly with the context length, is very likely to cause system-level Out-of-Memory (OOM).

2. Bandwidth Bound: The nature of autoregressive generation determines that a single Token prediction requires a full memory access of all weights (Memory-Bound). Under the 273 GB/s bandwidth provided by the M4 Pro, the theoretical throughput upper limit for hard reading 30GB weights is only ~9 tokens/s.

To break through the above bottlenecks, this paper proposes a multi-modal scheduling and compression framework. By introducing system-level I/O decoupling at the storage layer, orthogonal transformation to eliminate outliers at the feature layer, and parallel verification mechanism at the decoding layer, the execution graph of edge-side large models is completely reconstructed.


---
2. System Architecture and Memory Replacement Strategy

For the hardware topology (Unified Memory Architecture), the strategy of this paper first decouples and maps model weights in the physical space dimension.

2.1 Flash Scheduling Based on Page Fault Interception (SSD-RAM Tiering)

Drawing on the *LLM in a flash* mechanism proposed by Apple, this framework abandons the traditional Eager Loading mode and instead uses the underlying UNIX system call `mmap` for virtual memory mapping.

*   For MoE Architecture (taking 122B-A10B as an example): MoE models have inherent spatial sparsity. By injecting the `--mlock 0` parameter to disable physical memory hard locking, the Page Replacement authority is delegated to the Mach virtual memory manager. The framework aggregates Random I/O into large-block sequential reads through Row-Column Bundling. High-frequency called Router networks and shared experts reside in 48GB RAM (occupying about 20GB), while low-frequency experts reside in SSD. When a cold call occurs, continuous large-block I/O can minimize the P/E (Program/Erase) wear cycle of SSD.

*   For Dense Architecture: Due to the dense characteristics of the computing process, SSD paging will cause catastrophic I/O Thrashing. Therefore, Dense models must be further compressed to within the physical memory capacity through ultra-low bit quantization, and `--mlock 1` is used to force them to reside in memory.


---
3. Polar Orthogonal Residual Cache Compression (TurboQuant)

KV Cache expansion in long text processing is another core constraint. Traditional INT8/INT4 cache quantization introduces extremely high quantization noise. This framework introduces the TurboQuant algorithm proposed by *Zandieh & Mirrokni (ICLR 2026)* to achieve lossless context caching at an extremely low bit width (3-bit).

3.1 Polar Orthogonal Rotation (PolarQuant)

Activation Tensors usually have serious Outliers, leading to uneven distribution of conventional scalar quantization ranges. In the first stage of the algorithm, a random orthogonal matrix $\mathbf{R}$ is constructed to perform rotation transformation $\mathbf{X}' = \mathbf{X}\mathbf{R}$ on the input Key/Value vector $\mathbf{X}$. This isomorphic transformation does not change the inner product between vectors (i.e., Attention Score remains unchanged), but based on the Central Limit Theorem, it uniformly disperses the energy in the high-dimensional space to each dimension, forcing a highly regular Gaussian-like distribution. Based on this distribution, the Lloyd-Max static scalar quantizer can be directly applied to complete 2~3 bit compression without calculating and storing dynamic Scaling Factors.

3.2 QJL 1-bit Residual Compensation

To eliminate the biased estimation of inner product caused by ultra-low bit quantization, the second stage of the algorithm extracts the quantization residual matrix $\mathbf{E}$ generated in the first step. Using the Johnson-Lindenstrauss Lemma, a 1-bit random projection is performed on $\mathbf{E}$. In the Self-Attention calculation stage, this 1-bit feature is added as a compensation term, thereby achieving unbiased consistency of calculation results while maintaining the extreme compression rate (32K context occupies <1GB memory).


---
4. Extreme Information Entropy Compression: Incoherent 2-bit Quantization

Dense models (such as 108B) cannot safely reside in 48GB unified memory under 4-bit format. Therefore, they must be further compressed to 2-bit. Traditional quantization suffers from precision collapse at this bit width. This framework adopts the calibration paradigm of QuIP# (Quantization with Incoherence Processing) combined with Importance Matrix (Imatrix).

4.1 Randomized Hadamard Transform (RHT) to Eliminate Feature Skewness

Homologous to the logic of TurboQuant processing cache, QuIP# applies a Randomized Hadamard Transform in the form of Kronecker product to the weight matrix $\mathbf{W}$. This achieves Incoherence Processing and completely smooths out Channel-wise Spikes in the weight tensor.

4.2 E8 Lattice Quantization and Memory Ledger Reconstruction

The weights after incoherent processing conform to an ideal multi-dimensional symmetric distribution. At this time, applying the densest packed E8 Lattice Quantizer can achieve asymptotically optimal quantization distortion rate.

In practical engineering (such as conversion to `IQ2_XXS` format), the physical footprint of the 108B Dense model is sharply reduced from 54GB to **~27 GB**.

Physical Memory Distribution Ledger (taking 48GB node as an example):

*   OS/Kernel Mapping: ~8 GB

*  KV Cache (3-bit compressed): ~1.5 GB (supports ~40K Tokens)

*   Resident Weights (2-bit): ~27 GB

*   Redundant Safety Margin: ~11.5 GB (ensures zero SSD paging)


---
5. Parallel Verification Decoding to Break Through the Memory Access Bandwidth Ceiling

Although 2-bit compression solves the "capacity wall", the 273 GB/s memory bandwidth of the M4 Pro still limits the frame rate of autoregressive generation. According to arithmetic intensity calculation, the theoretical time-consuming to read 27GB weights to generate a single Token is about 0.1 seconds (10 tokens/s).

5.1 Draft-Free Speculative Decoding Architecture

To break through the von Neumann memory access bottleneck, this scheme abandons the traditional cascaded draft model that occupies additional memory and has unstable hit rate, and instead introduces a tree-based speculative mechanism based on EAGLE or Medusa architecture.

On top of the last layer of the main network, 3-5 extremely lightweight single-layer Feed-Forward Networks (FFN Heads) are tiled and connected. In a single forward propagation, these FFN heads reuse the hidden layer features of the main trunk and output multi-branch candidate Token prediction trees at time steps $t+1, t+2, ..., t+k$.

5.2 Throughput Gain Analysis

The system converts the continuous calculations required for multiple autoregressions into a parallel computing matrix in the form of a Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG). During the next full weight loading cycle of the main model, a one-time Parallel Verification is performed on the entire candidate tree.

*   Dense Models (108B level): The average Token acceptance rate per weight read-write cycle is increased to 2.5 ~ 3.0. The equivalent output throughput jumps from the baseline of 10 tokens/s to **25 ~ 28 tokens/s**.

*   Sparse Models (MoE 122B-A10B level): Combined with 2-bit quantization, the 10B expert weights activated in a single round are only **~2.5 GB**. The 273 GB/s bandwidth can support extremely high-frequency cyclic memory access. With parallel decoding, the theoretical throughput upper limit can reach the high-speed response range of **50 ~ 70 tokens/s**.


---
6. Experimental Design and Performance Evaluation

To rigorously verify the system-level gain of this framework under extreme hardware constraints, this study designs comprehensive benchmark tests and underlying telemetry experiments. The experimental benchmark platform is set as an Apple M4 Pro node equipped with 48GB unified memory and 2TB NVMe SSD. The evaluation indicators include end-to-end throughput, system synergy effect, underlying I/O loss, and generation latency distribution.

6.1 Baseline Comparisons and Throughput

This section compares the native inference engine framework (such as the standard `llama.cpp`, which relies on the operating system's native Swap mechanism to handle overflow memory) with the fusion framework proposed in this study.

Experiments select 108B Dense model and 122B-A10B MoE model, and record the Token generation speed (Tokens/s) under different context lengths (Context Length: 4K, 16K, 32K). The expected results will show that in the short context interval, the baseline framework's throughput decays rapidly to less than 1 token/s due to frequent page faults; in the long context interval above 16K, the baseline framework directly triggers OOM crash. In contrast, the framework in this paper stably maintains a throughput of 20+ tokens/s for Dense models and breaks through 50+ tokens/s for MoE models in the full context interval, showing absolute ability to cross the memory wall.

6.2 Ablation Study and System Synergy Analysis

To demonstrate the necessity and nonlinear gain of multi-dimensional optimization strategies, this study designs a progressive ablation experiment to strip off each core technical component:

1.  Configuration A (Only `mmap`-based SSD-RAM scheduling enabled): The system successfully avoids OOM, but with the increase of dialogue rounds, the uncompressed KV Cache quickly occupies physical memory, leading to a large number of model weights being squeezed into SSD, causing serious I/O bottlenecks and linear attenuation of throughput.

2.  Configuration B (`mmap` scheduling + TurboQuant cache compression): The long-context OOM and attenuation problems are eradicated, and the system memory state tends to be stable. However, limited by the memory access limit of pure autoregressive generation, its physical throughput is deadlocked at the memory bandwidth ceiling (~10 tokens/s).

3.  Configuration C (Complete framework of this paper: `mmap` + TurboQuant + parallel speculative decoding): Under this configuration, the system shows significant superlinear synergy ("1+1+1 > 3"). The reasoning logic is: TurboQuant and 2-bit extreme weight quantization release crucial physical memory space, and this "space dividend" becomes the premise for parallel speculative decoding (such as EAGLE tree branches) to reside in memory; the "bandwidth amplification effect" brought by parallel decoding, in turn, makes up for the occasional computational graph delay caused by SSD dynamic paging. Each technology is the foundation of each other and indispensable.

6.3 I/O Profiling and Write Amplification Suppression

One of the core pain points of edge-side large model landing is the irreversible loss of the physical life of solid-state drives. This experiment uses macOS `iostat` and Instruments DTrace tools to perform microsecond-level sampling of the underlying storage sector read and write during the entire inference cycle.

*   Traditional Mechanism Loss Evaluation: The chart will show that under the native operating system Swap mechanism, 100B-level models cause catastrophic system-level Page Thrashing. In a single 1000 Tokens long text generation, it is accompanied by hundreds of Gigabytes (GB) or even Terabytes (TB) level Write Amplification, which seriously overdraws the P/E cycle of SSD.

*   Suppression Efficacy of This Framework: Monitoring data will prove that after adopting the `mlock 0` dynamic scheduling and row-column bundled prefetching of this framework, only a short period of sequential read occurs in the Prefill/Warm-up phase. After entering the Steady-State Decoding phase, the disk read activity (KB/t) approaches zero. Compared with the baseline group, this framework reduces the cumulative SSD read-write load by more than 95%, fundamentally achieving absolute protection of the hardware life cycle.

6.4 Latency Distribution and Streaming Smoothness

The core user experience indicator of interactive AI depends on the smoothness of the output frame rate. This study draws boxplots and time series plots of the latency distribution of the entire inference link.

1.  Time to First Token (TTFT): The data will objectively present the slight compromise of this framework in the TTFT indicator. Since the system needs to perform block migration of cold data from SSD (Row-Column Bundled Loading) during the Prompt input phase, there may be a physical delay of hundreds of milliseconds in TTFT.

2.  Inter-Token Latency (ITL): After entering the streaming output phase, since the hot data has been stably locked in 48GB physical RAM by Mach VM, and the 3-bit KV Cache and 2-bit weights greatly alleviate bus congestion, the time series curve of ITL will show extremely low variance (Low Variance). This Jitter-free smooth streaming output is equivalent to constant high-frame-rate rendering in perception, establishing an extreme edge-side user experience.

7. Conclusion

This paper proposes a complete engineering paradigm for running 100B-parameter large language models on 48GB medium-capacity unified memory devices. The research shows that simply relying on the vertical upgrade of the hardware stack is not the only path for edge-side AI landing. Through in-depth joint design in system engineering dimensions such as storage layer mapping (flash cascading scheduling), feature layer preprocessing (orthogonal/Hadamard incoherent transformation), and decoding paradigm reconstruction (parallel verification), the framework in this paper successfully decouples the dual physical limitations of memory capacity and bandwidth. This paradigm effectively reduces SSD I/O wear, establishes the feasibility of low-latency inference of ultra-large-scale language models on the edge, and provides a highly repeatable implementation standard for the software-hardware co-optimization of edge computing architecture.
